{
  "style": "APA",
  "texts": [
    "And most importantly, can students transfer their creative approaches and understanding of how generative AI systems work from a computing education setting to other subjects in school, or even to their everyday lives outside school?",
    "As the questions posed above indicate, there is a research gap on how to teach generative AI with students as creators and designers, and how to foster students' ability to transfer these competences to the world they encounter outside school.",
    "Hence, future research should address whether students are able to retain their knowledge and competences about generative AI systems and if they are able to apply them in new contexts.",
    "Transfer of knowledge is crucial to education since knowledge about and interactions with AI systems generally aspires to have impact on contexts, such as students' lives outside school, which is quite different from the specific context of learning in computing education.",
    "When investigating the nature of students' transfer of knowledge, both the concept of near transfer (learning transfer to closely related contexts and performances) and the concept of far transfer (learning transfer to rather different contexts and performances) are relevant (Barnett & Ceci, 2002; Musaeus & Musaeus, 2024)."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "When investigating the nature of students' transfer of knowledge, both the concept of near transfer (learning transfer to closely related contexts and performances) and the concept of far transfer (learning transfer to rather different contexts and performances) are relevant (Barnett & Ceci, 2002; Musaeus & Musaeus, 2024)."
  ]
}